Maiharaji, Altine Gusau The Zamfara State Commissioner of Police, Usman Nagogo, has given a seven-day ultimatum to people who possess firearms illegally in the state to return them to the nearest police station. The spokesperson for the command, SP Mohammed Shehu, said in a statement that the commissioner had set up a Joint Task Force, headed by the Deputy Commissioner of Police in charge of Operations, to commence the seizure of weapons from unauthorised persons. The commissioner warned members of the public, including groups such as vigilance groups, town unions, hunters and watchmen, to desist from being in possession of firearms illegally. The statement added, “The operation will include cordoning off any premises, hideouts, dwelling houses or buildings or sites (completed or under construction) or any other location where these illegal/prohibited firearms are kept or on reasonable suspicion are believed to be kept. “Those in possession of such firearms are given seven days from August 13, 2020 to surrender them to the Task Force or any nearest police station. Area Commanders and DPOs are under strict instruction by the Commissioner of Police to carry out and enforce this directive in totality in their respective areas.” He also directed them to immediately convey a security stakeholders meeting to sensitise the public to this development. “The renewed commitment of the command to guarantee protection of lives and property across the state remains unequivocal and unwavering,” the commissioner added. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com